<TITLE> Budget session starts Thursday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 03 (bdnews24.com)The second session of the ninth parliament will run through to July 9, speaker Abdul Hamid has said. The decision came on Wednesday from the meeting of the Business Advisory Committee, which determines duration of every parliament session, at the parliament building. The second session, known as budget session, starts at 3pm on Thursday. The committee rejected the finance minister's proposal of passing the national budget on July 23 instead of June 30. The meeting, with the speaker presiding over, also decided that the House will hold 40 hours of discussion on proposed national budget for 2009-10 fiscal year. "As there is an obligation to pass the budget by June 30, the committee has not accepted the (finance minister's) proposal," Hamid told reporters after meeting. He said finance minister would place the budget on June 11 after the House convenes at 3pm. "The House will continue until July 9, but it can be stretched further considering the level of the proceedings," said Hamid. He said parliament would also sit on two SaturdaysJune 20 and June 27to hold 40 hours budget discussion. Usually, parliament is not convened on Friday and Saturday. As per the decision of the committee, except the two days (June 4 and June 11) parliament will sit at 4pm and continue until 9pm or 10pm every day. The question-answer session for the prime minister and the ministers would not take place in order to facilitate budget discussion. "If the prime minister wants, the weekly prime minister's question session will take place," said Hamid. Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, deputy leader of the House Syed Sajeda Chowdhury, law minister Shafiq Ahmed, deputy speaker Shawkat Ali, MPs Sheikh Fazlul Karim Selim, Suranjit Sengupta, chief whip Abdus Shahid, Md Rahmat Ali, Rashed Khan Menon, Md Fazle Rabbi Mian, and M K Anwar attended the meeting. Jamiruddin Sircar represented leader of the opposition Khaleda Zia at the meeting.
